<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-II-5-sols">
        <title><m>\S II.5</m>: Constructing <m>\Z</m> and <m>\Q</m></title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace=".25in">
                    <title>Motivation: Constructing Common Sets </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Equivalence relations play a large role in constructing many sets that we take for granted.
                            This section will give us an illustration of how the integers and rational numbers can be constructed
                            from the natural numbers using equivalence relations.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Constructing <m>\Z</m></title>
                    <introduction>
                        <p>
                            Define <m>\N_0 = \N \cup \{0\}</m>, and let <m>Z</m> be the relation on 
                            <m>(\N_0 \times \N_0) \times (\N_0 \times \N_0)</m> defined by 
                            <me>
                                (a,b) Z (c,d) \text{ iff } b+c = a+d
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </introduction>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                What element(s) are related to <m>(0,0)</m>?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>(0,0) Z (c,c)</m> for all <m>c \in \N_0</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Write down at least <m>3</m> other elements of <m>Z</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Examples includes <m>((0,2), (3,5))</m>, <m>((2,0), (6,4))</m>, and <m>((6,3), (3,0))</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                What integer do you think <m>(a,b) \in \N_0 \times \N_0</m> is meant to represent?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                It represents the integer <m>b-a</m>. 
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                               Explain why you think the relation <m>Z</m> was defined the way that it was.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                The relation <m>Z</m> forces <m>b-a = d-c</m>, so that writing the same integer in 
                                two different ways would still be considered the same (<m>0-2 = 4-6</m>).
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Verify that <m>Z</m> is an equivalence relation.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>(a,b) Z (a,b)</m> since <m>b+a = a + b</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                If <m>(a,b) Z (c,d)</m>, then <m>b+c = a + d</m>. Then it is also true that 
                                <m>d+ a = c +b</m>, so <m>(c,d) Z (a,b)</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                If <m>(a,b) Z (c,d)</m> and <m>(c,d) Z (e,f)</m>, then <m>b+c = a +d</m> and <m>d+e = c+f</m>.
                                Then it is also true that <m>d+e + b+c= a+d+ c+f</m>, or <m>b + e = a + f</m>, so 
                                <m>(a,b) Z (e,f)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                How can we use the equivalence relation <m>Z</m> to define elements of <m>\Z</m>?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Elements of <m>\Z</m> are equivalence classes of the equivalence relation <m>Z</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>


            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Constructing <m>\Q</m></title>
                    <introduction>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>Q</m> be the relation on 
                            <m>(\Z \times \Z \setminus \{0\}) \times (\Z \times \Z \setminus \{0\})</m> defined by 
                            <me>
                                (a,b) Q (c,d) \text{ iff } ad = bc
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </introduction>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                What element(s) are related to <m>(1,1)</m>?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>(1,1) Q (c,c)</m> for all <m>c \in \Z \setminus \{0\}</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Write down at least <m>3</m> other elements of <m>Q</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Examples include <m>((0,2), (0,5))</m>, <m>((2,4), (1,2))</m>, and <m>((-2,1), (-6,3))</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                What rational number do you think <m>(a,b) \in \Z \times \Z \setminus \{0\}</m> is meant to represent?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{a}{b}</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                               Explain why you think the relation <m>Q</m> was defined the way that it was.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                The relation <m>Q</m> forces <m>\frac{a}{b}= \frac{c}{d}</m>, so that writing the same rational number in 
                                two different ways would still be considered the same (<m>\frac{2}{4} = \frac{1}{2} </m>).
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Verify that <m>Q</m> is an equivalence relation.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>(a,b) Q (a,b)</m> since <m>ab = ba</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                If <m>(a,b) Q (c,d)</m> then <m>ad = bc</m>. Then it is also true that <m>cb = da</m>, so
                                <m>(c,d) Q (a,b)</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                If <m>(a,b) Q (c,d)</m> and <m>(c,d) Q (e,f)</m>, then <m>ad = bc</m> and <m>cf = de</m>. Then 
                                it is also true that <m>adcf= bcde</m>, and that <m>acf=bce</m> (since we know <m>d \neq 0</m>). If <m>c=0</m>,
                                then <m>a = e =0</m>, so <m>af=be</m>. If <m>c\neq0</m>, then we can divide <m>acf=bce</m> by <m>c</m> to get
                                <m>af = be</m>. So <m>(a,b) Q (e,f)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                How can we use the equivalence relation <m>Q</m> to define elements of <m>\Q</m>?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Elements of <m>\Q</m> are equivalence classes of the equivalence relation <m>Q</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>


        </worksheet>
